90–Deceased","1195–Female":"1195–Deceased","1190":"1190","before 1245":"before 1245","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1195":"1195","1293":"1293","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1312":"1312","1245":"1245","1232":"1232","1265":"1265","about 1220":"about 1220","about 1265":"about 1265","1306":"1306","Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, England","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Elye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Alyea  , a surname of French origin.","History: The Elyeas are descendants of Nicolas d'Ailly, a Huguenot from France (see   Alyea  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Alyea","meanings":["Americanized form of French <b>D'Ailly</b> or   Dailly  . Compare   Allee   2 and   Elyea  .","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with several variants, including <i>Allée</i>, and the original form <i>d'Ailly</i>). The Huguenot ancestor was Nicolas d'Ailly, who came from France to NY <i>c.</i> 1682 via the Netherlands and England and died in NJ <i>c.</i> 1700."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":4,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":39,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard De Elye was born about 1220, in Norwich, Norfolk, England, his father, Ralph de Ely, was 32 and his mother, Mrs. Ralph De Elye, was 27. He married Mrs Richard De Elye before 1245, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died about 1265, in England, at the age of 47."},"et":{"about 1220–about 1265":"umbes 1220–umbes 1265","1220–1265":"1220–1265","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1230–1312":"1230–1312","1232–1293":"1232–1293","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1245–1306":"1245–1306","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1195–Female":"1195–Surnud","1190":"1190","before 1245":"enne 1245","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1195":"1195","1293":"1293","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1312":"1312","1245":"1245","1232":"1232","1265":"1265","about 1220":"umbes 1220","about 1265":"umbes 1265","1306":"1306","Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, England","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1220–about 1265":"noin 1220–noin 1265","1220–1265":"1220–1265","1225–Male":"1225–Kuollut","1230–1312":"1230–1312","1232–1293":"1232–1293","1235–Male":"1235–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1245–1306":"1245–1306","1190–Male":"1190–Kuollut","1195–Female":"1195–Kuollut","1190":"1190","before 1245":"ennen vuotta 1245","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1195":"1195","1293":"1293","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1312":"1312","1245":"1245","1232":"1232","1265":"1265","about 1220":"noin 1220","about 1265":"noin 1265","1306":"1306","Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, England","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"about 1220–about 1265":"environ 1220–environ 1265","1220–1265":"1220–1265","1225–Male":"1225–Décédé","1230–1312":"1230–1312","1232–1293":"1232–1293","1235–Male":"1235–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1245–1306":"1245–1306","1190–Male":"1190–Décédé","1195–Female":"11